<div id="review_648900945" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/648900945" />
    <a title="David Bruns" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11890949-david-bruns"><img alt="David Bruns" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428414429p2/11890949.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/648900945?book_show_action=true">Jun 23, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Bruns" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Bruns" href="/user/show/11890949-david-bruns">David Bruns</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer648900945" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16327443488906574526">Manchester&apos;s book is a massive tome - 1300 pages - that provides a narrative history of 1932 to 1972. He starts with the Depression and ends with Watergate. It is worth the workout; however, if you can get the two volume version that is much easier to physically handle. <br/><br/>He does a fantastic job of putting each ear into perspective and getting behind the scenes into what made the country tick at each point in our history. For example, you get a rundown on what people were reading, wearing, watchin</span>
  <span id="freeText16327443488906574526" style="display:none">Manchester's book is a massive tome - 1300 pages - that provides a narrative history of 1932 to 1972. He starts with the Depression and ends with Watergate. It is worth the workout; however, if you can get the two volume version that is much easier to physically handle. <br /><br />He does a fantastic job of putting each ear into perspective and getting behind the scenes into what made the country tick at each point in our history. For example, you get a rundown on what people were reading, wearing, watching at the movies of TV and listening to on the radio. Beyond the breadth of topic, the amazing part of his writing is how he is able to offer this kind of depth on a consistent basis over the 40 year span.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16327443488906574526" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review648900945">
