<div id="review_7563836" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/7563836" />
    <a title="Snowfalcon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/465397-snowfalcon"><img alt="Snowfalcon" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/7563836?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Snowfalcon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Snowfalcon" href="/user/show/465397-snowfalcon">Snowfalcon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">anyone.</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer7563836" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6287900678381113789">I have read quite a bit of Manchester, primarily his biographies.<br/><br/>I found this to be a particularly poignant read these last few years. (It&apos;s a long book, 1300 pages, and I&apos;ve put it down and taken it up more than a few times in the last two or three years.) <br/><br/>I was drawn to it because of my interest in history. Typically my historical tastes tend toward the medieval and ancient, however when I dipped into this at a coffee shop just to kill time I was reminded of the very interesting way Manchester</span>
  <span id="freeText6287900678381113789" style="display:none">I have read quite a bit of Manchester, primarily his biographies.<br /><br />I found this to be a particularly poignant read these last few years. (It's a long book, 1300 pages, and I've put it down and taken it up more than a few times in the last two or three years.) <br /><br />I was drawn to it because of my interest in history. Typically my historical tastes tend toward the medieval and ancient, however when I dipped into this at a coffee shop just to kill time I was reminded of the very interesting way Manchester has of taking a range of events and personalities and arranging them so that they can be viewed from a new perspective. <br /><br />I found myself continuing to read it for a couple of reasons. First from a general curiousity. In history classes in school American History usually drew to a close around 1953 at the most recent. So the period from 1932 to 1972 which I was growing up in got very little treatment. I lived for part of that time, and grew up with those who had lived through those years, so I was eating it up as it was giving me perspective on my life and the lives of those near to me. Things I had heard about through popular culture were laid out for me. <br /><br />Add to that Manchester's perspective as a participant and often insider in the events he is relating. Yes, it's a bias. I don't mind bias as long as I'm clear what the author's bias is. Indeed that can add to a work.<br /><br />Finally, as Dickens put it "it was the best of times, it was the worst of times ... it was a time like unto our own" (my paraphrase) ... the past echoes into the present and while it can be debated if that was Manchester's intent, to be reading about the rise of Nazism, McCarthy, the Military Industrial Complex, Mitchell arguing as Nixon's Attorney General that there was a need for wire tapping without the current red tape, and more ... which have so many resonances in current events ... is a gift.<br /><br />The last two pages are well worth the effort sometimes necessary in the first 1298.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6287900678381113789" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

